			<pb n="1"/>
				<p rend="align(center)"><placeName>Cincin</placeName> <date>February 14 5613</date></p>
				<p>To the <addressee>Revd. I Leeser</addressee>.  Sir&#47;</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">I beg leave to inform you that the vestry room under our new<lb/> Synagogue at the corner of <placeName>6th St. &#38; Broadway</placeName> was <sic>opend</sic> for the 1st time for divine worship<lb/> on <add>Hebrew</add>&#44; On which <sic>ocasion</sic> the <persName>Revd. Mr. M Cohen</persName> late <add>Hebrew</add> of the Polish <add>Hebrew</add><lb/> cutter <add>&#63;</add> <placeName>London</placeName>&#44; was requested to read the prayers which he did&#44; and on the following<lb/> morng. he delivered a lecture in the English language&#44; and on <date>Saturday</date> last&#44; he did the<lb/> same in the german.  This gentlemn. is here for some time&#44; he is <sic>desireous</sic> to<lb/> obtain a situation&#44; as <add>Hebrew</add> Teacher and lecturer&#44; in this <sic>Contry</sic>&#44; he requests me<lb/> to mention this to you&#44; and to support his pretensions with the intent that<lb/> you will be good enough to place him through your Occidt. as a candidate<lb/> before the public in the above capacity.  <persName>Mr. Cohen</persName> is an entire stranger with<lb/> us&#44; he states that he is in <sic>posession</sic> of valuable testimonials from eminent<lb/> persons in <placeName>Europe</placeName>&#44; including one from the <persName>Rd. Dr. N Adler</persName> <sic>recomending</sic> him<lb/> &#38; so forth.  Our friends here were well pleased with his reading of the Prayers<lb/> &#38; the <add>Hebrew</add> which was exceedingly correct his lectures were arranged with<lb/> accuracy&#44; and if his &#8220;Teachings are not founded on the fundamental&#8221; Bulwarks of<lb/> our faith&#44; I am assured by those&#44; who are capable to pronounce an opinion&#44; that they<lb/> <del>are</del> were highly instructive&#44; and very interesting and well supported with the reasonings and<lb/> opinions of the best of our commentators.  <persName>Mr. C.</persName> does not pretend to be eloquent.<lb/>  It cannot be expected that every man can be a &#8220;<persName>Raphael</persName> or a &#8220;<persName>Jacobs</persName>&#44; yet this much<lb/> may be said in his favor.  That any congregation <sic>requireing</sic> a good teacher for their children<lb/> on agreeable <add>Hebrew</add> who understands what he says for their <add>Hebrew</add> an experienced scholar<lb/> <sic>posessing</sic> requisite attainments&#44; for expounding our sacred law&#44; &#38; &#38;&#44; this gent. will be<lb/> a great acquisition.  If the above request is compatible with the regulations of<lb/> the Occidet. be pleased to notice it.  I may mention that the article<lb/> headed Le Justus Milieu in the last <hi rend="underline">number</hi> was well recd by many in <placeName>Cin.</placeName> while to others it was not <sic>to</sic><lb/> acceptable.  The <persName>Revd I. Rosenfelt</persName> in particular has declared war to the knifer<add>&#63;</add> against<lb/> <persName>Mr. Matyer</persName> &#38; <persName>D. Myers</persName>.  Facts are stubborn things&#44; and not very palatable to those who<lb/> are regardless of the truth.  I am afraid that my letter which accompanied<lb/> the one of <persName>Messr. Matyer</persName> &#38; <persName>Myers</persName> will <hi rend="underline">be out of place</hi> in the next Occidt. unless<lb/> corrected by yourself&#44; should this be likewise your opinion&#44; I will not feel in<lb/> any way <sic>disapointed</sic> by its omission.  Our object is so far attained&#44;<lb/> I desire good will and peace with all men.  I remain yours very Respy.&#61;<persName role="author">Saml. Bruel</persName></p>
			<pb n="2"/>
				<p>To the <addressee>Rev. Isaac Leeser</addressee></p>
